Perhaps you could use the [history][1] api provided by `react-router` and leverage `withRouter` to create high order components for your `App` component, as well as any other components which need access to the history api. These higher order components will then be allowed to push to the browser&#39;s history.

Directly from the documentation:

&quot;*You can get access to the history object’s properties and the closest &lt;Route&gt;&#39;s match via the withRouter higher-order component. withRouter will pass updated match, location, and history props to the wrapped component whenever it renders*&quot;

Something along the lines of: (for `App.js`) 

    import React from &quot;react&quot;;
    import { withRouter } from &quot;react-router-dom&quot;;
    class App extends Component {
        ...
        onIndexChange(newIndex) {
            const profileType = this.state.profileType.toLowerCase();
            const routePath = `${profileType}/${newIndex}`;
            this.setState({activeIndex: newIndex});
            // assuming your newIndex correctly contains the new route
            this.props.history.push(newIndex);`
        }
        ...
    
    };

    export default withRouter(App);

**Note**: You can apply this technique to any component which needs access to the history api.


Hopefully that helps!


  [1]: https://reacttraining.com/react-router/web/api/history

